Title: High-level Perceptual Contours from a Variety of Low-level Physical Features  
Author: Brian M. Scassellati Supervisor: Prof. Lynn Andrea Stein 
Degree: Submitted in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the Degree of Bachelor of Science in Computer Science and Engineering and Master of Engineering in Electrical  
Note: Thesis  This work was supported by an award from the Bose Foundation, for which the author is most grateful.  
Affiliation: Engineering and Computer Science  
Date: January 10, 1995  
Abstract: Previous researchers have explored various methods of deriving edge information from luminance derivatives, color contrast, depth information, and textural patterns. However, no single one of these methods is sufficient for detecting all of the contour information that humans perceive. This thesis will be concerned with combining various existing methods of edge identification into a perceptual contour identifier, and the demonstration that the combination of these methods leads to improved contour processing on real-world images. 
