Reference-contexts: There have been a variety of techniques developed by computational researchers to deal with the problem of illusory contours. Guy and Medioni suggest using point extension fields to extend and complete line segments <ref> [GM94] </ref>. Their work has shown some capacity for recovering illusory contour information from figures such as the Kanizsa triangle and square. Kass, Witkin, and Terzopoulous have used active splines, or "snakes," for a variety of imaging tasks [KWT87]. <p> Both tasks will rely upon the same basic perceptual contour code with different back-end applications. We will use the physical characteristics from a Canny operator [Can83], Guy and Medioni's point field detectors <ref> [GM94] </ref>, a disparity estimator, and a textural processor. These edge detection methods will then by combined into a single contour identifier. The perceptual contours will be used to identify and segment objects from the background. 1 Once objects have been identified, each of the two tasks can operate independently.
